Sorry for the code not building, I fixed the build errors and tested in local CI. I was too anxious to get some progress after a very long hiatus and was a bit overwhelmed by having to address (the discussion involved in) both bmcweb and phosphor-health-monitor simultaneously (for the sensor names on DBus) for this to work at all.

What I was asking is I would like to use this change to restart the discussion on what are good names for the utilization sensors' DBus objects. Previously there was a concern that "CPU_Kernel" and "CPU_User" show up in the WebUI and confuse the user as they look like host CPU usage and someone mentioned prefixing the objects with "BMC", but if I remember correctly there were concerns over prefixing too. With contradicting comments on prefixing the sensor names with "BMC" I'm not sure this is what I can solve alone, so I'd rather post this change with the original bad names and get this discussed.

Regarding the handler code in the change, hopefully I have made it simple and clear enough this time.

The naming issue would affect not just the BMC CPU metric, but other metrics as well. So I would appreciate it if there is one unified voice on the naming. What names would you suggest?

Don't get overwhelmed.  I'm happy to have the conversation in one place, feel free to pick one review, and tag the right people in it.

> 
> What I was asking is I would like to use this change to restart the discussion on what are good names for the utilization sensors' DBus objects. Previously there was a concern that "CPU_Kernel" and "CPU_User" show up in the WebUI and confuse the user as they look like host CPU usage and someone mentioned prefixing the objects with "BMC", but if I remember correctly there were concerns over prefixing too. With contradicting comments on prefixing the sensor names with "BMC" I'm not sure this is what I can solve alone, so I'd rather post this change with the original bad names and get this discussed.

This exact concern is why we generally use associations for this kind of thing.  As a matter of extension, lets say we had the host CPU usage available as well, given that people might want to pick their sensor name, how would we differentiate between the BMC CPU usage and the host CPU usage?

> 
> Regarding the handler code in the change, hopefully I have made it simple and clear enough this time.
> 
> The naming issue would affect not just the BMC CPU metric, but other metrics as well. So I would appreciate it if there is one unified voice on the naming. What names would you suggest?

I don't really think we should use names at all.  In general, Name should ideally be user-configurable and user-facing;  We've been burned before by hardcoding a specific name, then a system needed to pick a different name, because name is user-facing.  We need a generic way to describe "this is the CPU usage for this component" which in general we use associations, this would just be a specific association.

On the question of setting up Association in an Entity-Manager-based system:

According to discussion on Discord, one solution is to add a BMC to a board .JSON file:

stwcx — 12/30/2021
I suppose that entirely depends on how you lay out your system data.  If the BMC is on the mainboard, then I would expect it to be in the board JSON.  If the BMC is on a card (such as a DC-SCM) I would expect the card to have its own EEPROM and you should define a JSON for that card.

Alatar — 01/05/2022
Is it work with adding "xyz.openbmc_project.Invntory.Item.Bmc" interface to board object? If this solves your issue, the it's fine without separate object.

With the above method (BMC in board JSON), the Board DBus object will have the BMC interface, as follows (Probe set to "TRUE" for testing in QEMU):

  {
    "Name": "SUPER_BOARD",
    "Probe": "TRUE",
    "Type": "Board",
    "xyz.openbmc_project.Inventory.Item.Bmc": {},
    "xyz.openbmc_project.Inventory.Decorator.Asset": {},
    "xyz.openbmc_project.Inventory.Connector.Slot": {},
    ...
  }

When picked up by Entity-Manager, the following object is created:

  # busctl introspect xyz.openbmc_project.EntityManager /xyz/openbmc_project/inventory/system/board/SUPER_BOARD

  xyz.openbmc_project.Inventory.Connector.Slot      interface -         -            -
  xyz.openbmc_project.Inventory.Decorator.Asset     interface -         -            -
  xyz.openbmc_project.Inventory.Decorator.FruDevice interface -         -            -
  xyz.openbmc_project.Inventory.Decorator.Ipmi      interface -         -            -
  xyz.openbmc_project.Inventory.Item.Bmc            interface -         -            -
  xyz.openbmc_project.Inventory.Item.Board          interface -         -            -

This allows phosphor-health-monitor to create Associations which will be used by this change to find the utilization sensors. From the perspective of one utilization sensor:

  # busctl get-property xyz.openbmc_project.HealthMon /xyz/openbmc_project/sensors/utilization/CPU_Kernel xyz.openbmc_project.Association.Definitions Associations
  a(sss) 1 "bmc" "bmc_diagnostic_data" "/xyz/openbmc_project/inventory/system/board/SUPER_BOARD"

From the perspective of the Board (this is the output of "step 3" in this change)

  # busctl get-property xyz.openbmc_project.ObjectMapper /xyz/openbmc_project/inventory/system/board/SUPER_BOARD/bmc_diagnostic_data xyz.openbmc_project.Association endpoints
as 19 "/xyz/openbmc_project/sensors/utilization/CPU" "/xyz/openbmc_project/sensors/utilization/CPU_Kernel" "/xyz/openbmc_project/sensors/utilization/CPU_User" 
"/xyz/openbmc_project/sensors/utilization/Storage_RW" ... "/xyz/openbmc_project/i2cstats/i2c_14"


This change can work with both the setup mentioned above (BMC inventory interfaces and Board/Chassis interfaces in a same DBus object.) or having the BMC as a separate .json config file.

GetSubTreeType and GetObjectType are exactly the same as is used by a few other headers in bmcweb, for cleaning up those lines I tried to reuse ones from existing files:

* GetSubTreeType is defined in openbmc_dbus_rest.hpp, sensors.hpp, managers.hpp. The latter two are an alias of the type in openbmc_dbus_rest.hpp. So I am including openbmc_dbus_rest.hpp.
* GetObjectType is defined dbus_utility.hpp, openbmc_dbus_rest.hpp, account_service.hpp, certificate_service.hpp, and virtual_media.hpp. However: in dbus_utility.hpp and openbmc_dbus_rest.hpp the alias is local to a few functions. The rest are handler files that are unrelated to ManagerDiagnosticData. So I'm not including them but rather repeat the GetObjectType alias in this file.
* Replaced SensorVariantType with dbus::utility::DbusVariantType defined in dbus_utility.hpp.
* Removed EndpointType aliase because it is basic enough.
* Removed EndpointVariantType because by using sdbusplus::asio::getProperty similarly to 44019, the variant container is not needed.

Please don't forward declare methods in an implementation file.  It implies that code needs to be moved around to be more organized, although in this case I suspect that they can just be removed.

Also, no need to call out "step 1, 2", ect.  They have no context in the code.

Added a check for '/' for more precise checking. But the "do not call by name" is what I can resolve before a consensus on how to identify different BMC metrics is settled.

I think these specific-named resources are in essence similar to other hard-coded string constants, and they are guaranteed by the daemons providing those strings, for example:
* `/xyz/openbmc_project/state/chassis0` in chassis.hpp is provided by `x86-power-control`
* `/xyz/openbmc_project/Intrusion` in chassis.hpp is provided by IntrusionSensor in `dbus-sensors`
